metadata.name: fxVase #75
metadata.description:
Sculpt, glaze, and fire your own virtual pottery, then mint it on the blockchain to share with the world. This interactive tool allows for an astounding range of expressive sculptures to be rendered in real time and saved in HD. It was written from scratch with vanilla JavaScript and WebGL.

Standalone Controls

Mouse or Touch to Control View
1 - Save Image
2 - Toggle Free Cam
3 - Toggle Frame
4 - Toggle Edit Mode
5 - Toggle Animate

metadata.name: Giza #34
metadata.description:
Tried to catch a poetic atmosphere working on this generative representation of the pyramids of Giza.
Built by thousands of humans during tens of years thousands years ago they're now generated in seconds with millions of dots by a javascript algorithm.
That's were knowledge has led us !

Features
 - Time: Day (probability 1/2) / Night (probability 1/2)
 - Mode: Dark (probability 5/6) / Light (probability 1/6)
 - Number of pyramids
 - Background dunes
 - Global ligthness
 - Sun/Moon shine
 - generative color palette

Only Javascript / No library used

metadata.name: Anachronous #141
metadata.description:
This project is about the exploration of chaotic structures created with lines and blurry silhouettes. They work together to make the shapes emerge without revealing them completely and create dark and light areas that compose a feeling of depth and weight to the scene.

Some pieces are chaotic, some more ordered. Some have strong compositions, some don't. By zooming in on the details we can let our mind wander and start seeing shapes.

Best experienced in full-screen.

Press S to take a screenshot
Press M to take a high resolution screenshot
Press H to take a higher resolution screenshot (may not work for some devices)

WARNING: Project is using webgl, it may not work on some older devices.

Original artwork by William Watkins Â· Lyon, 2022

metadata.name: Charcoal Brutalism #49
metadata.description:
Based on a similar technique as "Charcoal Landscapes", using lines limited to 8 possible directions, this work is about the repetition of patterns at different scales and the use of negative spaces.
The texture created from the noise combined with the structures that emerges from this algorithm create a look similar to the brutalist architecture of the last century.

There are 10 scale variations but with almost infinite possible outcomes.
Inverted colours have a small chance of dropping.

Original artwork by William Watkins Â· Lyon, 2022

metadata.name: De/Frag #305
metadata.description:
De/Frag is an homage to a classic algorithm in early computer art: Flood Fill. As a teenager in the late '80s, and without any literature, I spent weeks implementing a version for my very own drawing program for the Atari XL. It was the first non-trivial (to me) algorithm which made me want to learn more about data structures, the concept of recursion, divide-and-conquer...

Even though Flood Fill was available in most commercial drawing & office apps of the time, I gained a deep appreciation of the algorithm by building it from scratch myself. 30+ years later I know its aesthetic possibilities are still far from exhausted. This is an invitation for re-exploration by others too!

As with many design algorithms, my primary interest isn't even the final result, but observing the inner workings. I massively slowed down and time-sliced the process for this piece. I do recommend giving each of these unique versions some time to allow them to evolve their ever-changing patterns (Note: each piece never loops!).

metadata.name: Angular Variations (Holding Space) #185
metadata.description:
Angular Variations. Holding space for transitions. Once minted the lines maintain their design while the spaces between adjust to accommodate changes in canvas size.

There are no rarity attributes assigned to this artwork, its value is intended to be determined by viewer aesthetic alone.

This artwork was created using p5js.

metadata.name: Ichigo #350
metadata.description:
This generator is named 'Ichigo' (è‹º/ ã„ã¡ã”), the Japanese word for 'strawberry'. 

Seeing each iteration from a suitable distance, small dots (to me, reminiscent of strawberry seeds) overlay different sequences of geometric repetitions, implying a sense of texture, grittiness and irregularity. 

By looking closer however, it becomes apparent to the viewer that the majority of the composition is in fact government by orderly elements, in this case grids of dots. 

This discovery invites the viewer to consider the output in front of them at different levels, near and far. At what point do you feel the dots begin to dissolve into a texture? When do you stop noticing the dots and instead begin to perceive the overall composition?

These questions are posed in a similar fashion as with meditation; at what point does something become something else? When does an in-breath become an out-breath and vice versa? 

Contemplation on simple questions like these can open a small portal into stillness and mindfulness by taking time to slowly observe our responses. 

23 palettes are included, each named after different areas of Tokyo. 

Press 'S' to download a full size 6000px x 6000px PNG output. 

As always, much gratitude and enjoy your piece.
